    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. it sounds pretty risky though. are there any specific parts of that wording that feel particularly \"hidden\" or like they're designed to catch someone off guard? like, is there anything in there that isn't immediately obvious to someone who isn't a lawyer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The part that might seem a bit \"hidden\" or tricky is the phrase \"including recklessness or willful misconduct.\" This means that even if you didn't intend to cause harm, but did something that's considered reckless or intentionally wrong, you're still held responsible. It's not just the mistakes or oversights; it's anything that shows a disregard for the proper execution of your duties. The phrase \"arising out of or occurring in connection with the performance of services\" broadens the scope significantly, indicating that any issue related to your work could trigger the indemnification clause, not just direct actions or decisions. This part of the wording is designed to cover a wide range of scenarios, potentially stretching the responsibility to cover more than you might expect. It's always a good idea to discuss these terms with a legal professional to fully understand your obligations and risks.",
